Jubilee politicians in Kisii county continue to meet in schools, despite a ban by Education CS Fred Matiang&rsquo;i.The politicians have held meetings at Gianchere, Tendere, Sameta and Kenyoro secondary schools. The latest meeting was held on Sunday at Sameta, where Jubilee leaders led by Kisii Senator Chris Obure met more than 1, 000 teachers to woo them to support President Uhuru Kenyatta.Jubilee branch chairman Samuel Nyairo said the meetings take place on Sundays. But Sameta and Tendere are boarding schools and students were in class during the meeting.On Monday, Matiang&rsquo;i appeared to defy his own directive when he visited schools with politicians to distribute Sh36 million cheques.He was accompanied by Jubilee politicians including Mary Otara (woman representative), MPs Jimmy Angwenyi (Kitutu Chache North), Zebedeo Opore (Bonchari), Simon Ogari (Bomachoge Chache) and nominated Senator Hosea Onchwangi. The legislators talked politics.